The paper deals with the concept of sparsification, which is closely linked to the Exponential Time Hypothesis, and extends it to capture subexponential time approximation. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Computational Complexity (cs.CC) sub-category. Additionally, the paper deals with several fundamental optimization problems, such as Max Independent Set, Min Dominating Set, Min Feedback Vertex Set, and Min Set Cover, which are typically studied in the Discrete Mathematics (cs.DM) and Graph Theory (cs.GT) sub-categories. The development of a new tool for inapproximability also suggests that the paper may belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. Finally, the use of sparsification techniques in the paper suggests that it may also belong to the Computational Geometry (cs.CG) sub-category.
